}

// Root.js
import Server from './Server';
import World from './World';

const Root = {
  server: null,
  world: null,
  init: function() {
    this.server = new Server(this);
    this.world = new World(this);

    // Additional initialization here if necessary
  }
};

Root.init();

export default Root;
```

In both examples, the key components are defined and imported properly. The `Root` object has an `init` method that is responsible for instantiating the server and world objects once everything has been fully defined. This way, you ensure that when the server and world constructors are called, they receive the complete `Root` object, which includes fully instantiated `server` and `world` properties.

Make sure to replace `'./Server'` and `'./World'` with the actual relative paths to your module files. These are just placeholders for illustration.

Remember, actual implementation details may vary depending on your project structure, the ES module system or CommonJS you're using, and if you're utilizing any frameworks or libraries.

